# ARM64 Instruction Encoding
# All enc_* functions are pure: parameters -> 32-bit instruction word (as i64).
# They use _encode_field(val, width, shift) to place bit fields.
# Reference: ARM Architecture Reference Manual for A-profile architecture.
# All operate on 64-bit (X) registers (sf=1) unless noted.
# [src: arm64.aria]

# --- Move Wide ---

@fn enc_movz
@sig (rd: i64, imm16: i64, hw: i64) -> i64
@source_file src/codegen/arm64.aria
@source_line 84
@purpose MOVZ: Rd = imm16 << (hw * 16), zeroing other bits. First step in loading large immediates. hw selects which 16-bit halfword (0-3).
@notes Encoding: sf=1 opc=10 100101 hw imm16 Rd. Base = 0xD2800000.

---

@fn enc_movk
@sig (rd: i64, imm16: i64, hw: i64) -> i64
@source_file src/codegen/arm64.aria
@source_line 91
@purpose MOVK: Rd[hw*16 +: 16] = imm16, keeping other bits unchanged. Used after MOVZ to set additional 16-bit chunks.
@notes Encoding: sf=1 opc=11 100101 hw imm16 Rd. Base = 0xF2800000.

---

@fn enc_movn
@sig (rd: i64, imm16: i64, hw: i64) -> i64
@source_file src/codegen/arm64.aria
@source_line 97
@purpose MOVN: Rd = ~(imm16 << (hw * 16)). Used for small negative constants (e.g., -1 = MOVN x0, #0, 0).
@notes Encoding: sf=1 opc=00 100101. Base = 0x92800000. Used in runtime for ~15 (alignment mask) and -1 (fd for mmap).

